s their 11th championship title overall and their second title in succession.\n\n==Results==\n===First round===\n\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 30 July 1967\n| round =  First round\n| team1 = [[Young Irelands GAA|Young Irelands]]\n| score = 4-12 - 3-05\n| team2 = [[\u00c9ire \u00d3g GAA (Kilkenny)|\u00c9ire \u00d3g]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 30 July 1967\n| round =  First round\n| team1 = [[Erin's Own GAA (Kilkenny)|Erin's Own]]\n| score = 3-10 - 3-08\n| team2 = [[Rower-Inistioge GAA|Rower-Inistioge]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 30 July 1967\n| round =  First round\n| team1 = [[Thomastown GAA|Thomastown]]\n| score = 3-05 - 1-09\n| team2 = [[St. Lachtain's GAA|St. Lachtain's]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n\n===Second round===\n\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 6 August 1967\n| round =  Second round\n| team1 = [[Bennettsbridge GAA|Bennettsbridge]]\n| score = 4-10 - 5-06\n| team2 = [[Young Irelands GAA|Young Irelands]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 6 August 1967\n| round =  Second round\n| team1 = [[Thomastown GAA|Thomastown]]\n| score = 2-10 - 2-05\n| team2 = [[Tullogher-Rosbercon GAA|Tullogher]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 20 August 1967\n| round =  Second round\n| team1 = [[Erin's Own GAA (Kilkenny)|Erin's Own]]\n| score = 3-11 - 1-08\n| team2 = [[James Stephens GAA|James Stephens]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = \n}}\n\n===Semi-finals===\n\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 8 October 1967\n| round =  Semi-final\n| team1 = [[Bennettsbridge GAA|Bennettsbridge]]\n| score = 2-13 - 0-12\n| team2 = [[Erin's Own GAA (Kilkenny)|Erin's Own]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = J Murphy (Tullogher)\n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 8 October 1967\n| round =  Semi-final\n| team1 = [[Thomastown GAA|Thomastown]]\n| score = 4-12 - 5-09\n| team2 = [[St. Senan's GAA|St. Senan's]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = J Murphy (Tullogher)\n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 22 October 1967\n| round =  Semi-final replay\n| team1 = [[Thomastown GAA|Thomastown]]\n| score = 2-09 - 1-10\n| team2 = [[St. Senan's GAA|St. Senan's]]\n| report = \n| goals1 = \n| goals2 = \n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = T Ryall\n}}\n\n===Final===\n\n{{footballbox collapsible\n| date = 12 November 1967\n| round = Final\n| team1 = [[Bennettsbridge GAA|Bennettsbridge]]\n| score = 3-10 - 1-04\n| team2 = [[Thomastown GAA|Thomastown]]\n| goals1 = P Moran 1-6, J Kinsella 1-1, T Kelly 1-0, P Treacy 0-2, J Carroll 0-1.\n| goals2 = J Murphy 1-0, S Kearney 0-1, V Kirby 0-1, J Kelly 0-1, B O'Sullivan 0-1.\n| stadium = [[Nowlan Park]], [[Kilkenny]]\n| referee = T Ryall\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kilkenny Senior Hurling Championship}}\n\n[[Category:1967 senior hurling county championships|Kilkenny Senior Hurling Championship]]\n[[Category:Kilkenny Senior Hurling Championship]]\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 3-10 \u2192 3\u201310 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_Kilkenny_Senior_Hurling_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Mingma Gyabu Sherpa", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|image = \n[[File:Mingma Gyabu.jpg|thumb|Photo of Mingma Gyabu at Everest Basecamp 2018]]\n|name = Mingma Gyabu Sherpa \n|other_names = Mingma David Sherpa \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|05|16}}\n|birth_place = [[[[Taplejung District|Taplejung]], [[Nepal]]]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|known_for = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mingma Gyabu Sherpa''' aka Mingma David (b. 16 May 1989) is a Nepalese [[Mountaineering|mountaineer]] and renowned rescue crew. Mingma Gyabu is the youngest person to climb the all 14 main 8000m peaks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma G. |title=14 Peak climber |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244/ |website=https://english.khabarhub.com/ |publisher=Khabarhub}}</ref> He also holds the Guinness World Record for the title of [https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/85291-fastest-time-to-climb-mount-everest-and-k2/ \"Fastest time to climb Everest and K2\"], he climbed first and second highest peak in the world with in 61 day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma Gyabu |title=Fastest Everest and K2 |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2/ |website=https://thehimalayantimes.com/ |publisher=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nTill the date 43 climbers has made successful ascents of all 14 [[Eight-thousander|eight thousanders]] including Mingma Gyabu. Among all 14 peaks above 8000m, Mingma climbed eight of them with [[Nirmal Purja]] as a climbing Sherpa in 2019.\n\n'''Name of the Mountains climbed by Mingma Gyabu:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No.!! Peak (Height) !! Year (Season)\n|-\n|1.||Everest (8848).    || 2010 (Spring)\n|-\n|2.||K2 (8611 m).    || 2014 (Summer), 2018 (Summer)\n|-\n|3.||Kangchenjunga (8586 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|4.||Lhotse (8516 m).    ||2018 (Spring)\n|-\n|5.||Makalu (8485 m).    ||2014 (Spring)\n|-\n|6.||Cho Oyu (8201 m).    ||2011 (Autumn)\n|-\n|7.||Dhaulagiri (8167 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|8.||Manaslu (8163 m).    ||2012 (Autumn), 2019 (Autumn)\n|-\n|9.||Nanga Parbat (8125 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|10.||Annapurna I (8091 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|11.||Gasherbrum I (8068 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|12.||Broad Peak (8047 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|13.||Gasherbrum II (8035 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|14.||Shisha Pangma (8027 m).    ||2019 (Autumn)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bastola |first1=Eak Raj |title=Dreaming high: Getting atop the Mt. Everest |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244 |website=english.khabarhub.com |publisher=Khabarhub |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pokheral |first1=Rajan |title=Mingma Gyabu sets world record for fastest ascents of Everest, K2\n|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2 |\n|accessdate=6 April 2020 |agency=The Himalayan Times |issue=New Paper |publisher=The Himalayan Times |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sherpa_summiters_of_Mount_Everest]]\n[[Category:Nepalese_mountain_climbers]]\n[[Category:Eight-thousanders]]\n[[Category:K2]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|image = \n[[File:Mingma Gyabu.jpg|thumb|Photo of Mingma Gyabu at Everest Basecamp 2018]]\n|name = Mingma Gyabu Sherpa \n|other_names = Mingma David Sherpa \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|05|16}}\n|birth_place = [[[[Taplejung District|Taplejung]], [[Nepal]]]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|known_for = [[Mountaineering]]\n}}\n\n'''Mingma Gyabu Sherpa''' aka Mingma David (b. 16 May 1989) is a Nepalese [[Mountaineering|mountaineer]] and renowned rescue crew. Mingma Gyabu is the youngest person to climb the all 14 main 8000m peaks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma G. |title=14 Peak climber |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244/ |website=https://english.khabarhub.com/ |publisher=Khabarhub}}</ref> He also holds the Guinness World Record for the title of [https://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/85291-fastest-time-to-climb-mount-everest-and-k2/ \"Fastest time to climb Everest and K2\"], he climbed first and second highest peak in the world with in 61 day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherpa |first1=Mingma Gyabu |title=Fastest Everest and K2 |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/mingma-gyabu-sets-world-record-for-fastest-ascents-of-everest-k2/ |website=https://thehimalayantimes.com/ |publisher=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\nTill the date 43 climbers has made successful ascents of all 14 [[Eight-thousander|eight thousanders]] including Mingma Gyabu. Among all 14 peaks above 8000m, Mingma climbed eight of them with [[Nirmal Purja]] as a climbing Sherpa in 2019.\n\n'''Name of the Mountains climbed by Mingma Gyabu:'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S.No.!! Peak (Height) !! Year (Season)\n|-\n|1.||Everest (8848).    || 2010 (Spring)\n|-\n|2.||K2 (8611 m).    || 2014 (Summer), 2018 (Summer)\n|-\n|3.||Kangchenjunga (8586 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|4.||Lhotse (8516 m).    ||2018 (Spring)\n|-\n|5.||Makalu (8485 m).    ||2014 (Spring)\n|-\n|6.||Cho Oyu (8201 m).    ||2011 (Autumn)\n|-\n|7.||Dhaulagiri (8167 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|8.||Manaslu (8163 m).    ||2012 (Autumn), 2019 (Autumn)\n|-\n|9.||Nanga Parbat (8125 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|10.||Annapurna I (8091 m).    ||2019 (Spring)\n|-\n|11.||Gasherbrum I (8068 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|12.||Broad Peak (8047 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|13.||Gasherbrum II (8035 m).    ||2019 (Summer)\n|-\n|14.||Shisha Pangma (8027 m).    ||2019 (Autumn)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bastola |first1=Eak Raj |title=Dreaming high: Getting atop the Mt. Everest |url=https://english.khabarhub.com/2019/06/11244 |website=english.khabarhub.com |publisher=Khabarhub |accessdate=6 April 