Music Charts|Polish Airplay Charts]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pifpaf.com.pl/airplay/lista_38_2000.html |title=Polish Airplay Charts \u2013 Lista krajowa 38/2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010304030048/http://www.pifpaf.com.pl/airplay/lista_38_2000.html |archivedate=March 4, 2001 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|13|date=20000813|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Spain|9|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|14|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|17|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|5|date=20000813|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 20, 2012}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKrandb|2|date=20000813|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrandbhiphop|3|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardpopsongs|3|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 2, 2014}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrhythmic|1|artist=Janet Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 2, 2014}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2000)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Belgium (Ultratop 50 Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2000|title=Rapports annuels 2000|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|language=French|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| 63\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/2000|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 2000|publisher=Dutch Top 40|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 78\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=2000&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 2000|publisher=[[Dutch Charts|MegaCharts]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n| 91\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=2000 |title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 2000 |accessdate=August 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304120640/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=2000 |archivedate=March 4, 2009}}</ref>\n| 18\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2000/hot-r-and-and-b-hip-hop-songs|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs \u2013 Year-End 2000|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| 29\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Janet Jackson|title=Doesn't Really Matter|relyear=2000|certyear=2000|award=Silver |accessdate=June 5, 2015}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Janet Jackson|title=Doesn't Really Matter|relyear=2000|certyear=2000|award=Gold |accessdate=June 5, 2015|salesamount=699,273|salesref=<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ghMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64 |title=Best-Selling Records of 2000 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=February 10, 2001 |accessdate=June 5, 2015 |page=64 |issn=0006-2510|volume=113|number=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://jj-cs.tumblr.com/most-downloaded-songs-in-the-us |title= Janet Jackson\u2019s most downloaded songs in the U.S. |work=JNTSRB |accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|janet-jackson|doesnt-really-matter}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Janet Jackson singles}}\n\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:Janet Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Janet Jackson]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n[[Category:Electropop songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2000 single by Janet Jackson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Doesn't Really Matter\n| cover      = Janet Jackson - Doesn't Really Matter.png\n| alt        = Jackson is seen hugging Eddie Murphy's character, Sherman Klump, while surrounded by the Klump family. The text above reads JANET JACKSON \u2013 DOESN'T REALLY MATTER\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Janet Jackson]]\n| album      = [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack]] ''and'' [[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2000|5|21|mf=y}}\n| format     = \n*[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = Flyte Tyme, [[Edina, Minnesota]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n<!--Do not add unsourced genres-->\n| length     = 4:18\n| label      = \n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     = \n*Janet Jackson\n*James Harris III\n*Terry Lewis\n| producer   = \n*[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n*Janet Jackson\n| prev_title = [[Girlfriend/Boyfriend]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\n\"'''Doesn't Really Matter'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Janet Jackson]] for the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2000 film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]''.<ref name=\"KlumpsMTV>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428172/20000523/dmx.jhtml|title=LL, Sisqo, Jay-Z, Foxy, DMX, More For \"Klumps\"|website=[[MTV News]]|date=May 23, 2000|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> The song was released as a [[Single (music)|single]] in May 21, 2000, after an unfinished version leaked to radio. \"Doesn't Really Matter\" is a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] song that speaks about loving a person for who they are and disregarding their physical appearance. It was based on an incomplete poem Jackson had written, which was later applied to her character in the film. The song was a contrast from the dark tone of prior album ''[[The Velvet Rope]]'', returning to a brighter and more contemporary sound.\n\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" received positive reception, called \"impossibly catchy\" and \"classic pop\". It became Jackson's ninth number-one single in the United States and stayed atop the chart for three weeks. It was Jackson's twenty-first single to be certified, which ranked her as the second female artist with the most certified singles. The single fared well internationally, reaching number five in the United Kingdom, and peaking within the top-ten in Italy and Denmark. It attained a silver certification in the United Kingdom, and allowed Jam and Lewis to receive a [[Grammy]] nomination for [[Producer of the Year]]. The song was later included in two of Jackson's greatest hits collections, ''[[Number Ones (Janet Jackson album)|Number Ones]]'' and ''[[Icon: Number Ones]]''.\n\nThe [[music video]], directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], resembles an [[abstract art|abstract]], futuristic environment based on Japanese culture. In addition to clips from the movie, it features advanced technology, morphing clothes, and a dance sequence on a levitating platform. The video had a reported cost of over $2.5 million, being one of the [[List of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos]] of all time. Its accolades include \"Outstanding Music Video\" and \"Most Stylish Music Video\" at the [[VH1]] Fashion Awards. The song was performed on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' and the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]], the latter regarded as one of the leading performances of Jackson's career.\n\nA slightly modified version of the song appeared on Jackson's seventh [[album]] ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]''. \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was considered to influence music videos from [[Britney Spears]], [[Jessica Simpson]] and [[Cassie (singer)|Cassie]]. The video was the first by director Joseph Kahn to feature Japanese themes and imagery, which he later used frequently following its popularity. Actress [[Jenna Dewan]] made one of her debut appearances in the video, crediting Jackson for the experience and platform to star in the dance film ''[[Step Up (film)|Step Up]]''. [[Rihanna]]'s \"Watch n' Learn\" was likened to the song, and it was also covered by Japanese singer [[Hitomi Shimatani]] as \"Papillon\".\n\n==Background and development==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" was written and produced by [[Janet Jackson]], [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]] as the theme for the [[Universal Pictures]] film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'', starring Jackson and actor [[Eddie Murphy]].<ref name=\"LinerNotes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=[[Janet Jackson]]|year=2000|type=booklet|publisher=[[Def Jam Records]]|id=314 562 846-2|location=New York City}}</ref> She portrays Professor Denise Gaines in the film, the love interest of [[The Nutty Professor (character)|Sherman Klump]], who is one of many characters portrayed by Murphy.<ref name=\"KlumpsMTV\"/> When asked to contribute a single for the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|movie's soundtrack]], Jackson stated that she would consider if she found an appropriate song.<ref name=\"Bronson\">{{cite book|last=Bronson|first=Fred|year=2003|title=Billboard's Hottest Hot 100 Hits|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Books]]|edition=3|page=902|isbn=0823077381}}</ref> The single would allow Jackson to continue releasing music, while simultaneously devoting time to her film career.<ref>{{cite book|date=July 21\u201323, 2000|title=Action Jackson|work=[[USA Weekend]]|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|date=November 2000|title=Janet at the Crossroads|work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]|page=181}}</ref> To help inspire Jackson, director [[Peter Segal]] brought a rough cut of the film to Flyte Tyme Studios where the singer was recording her seventh album, ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]''. She decided to write an uptempo love song rather than a [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]], inspired by Segal finding her love for Murphy's unattractive character in the film convincing.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/>\n\n{{listen|pos=right|filename=Janet - Doesn't Really Matter.ogg |title=\"Doesn't Really Matter\"|description=The lyrics were initially written by Jackson as a poem, before being implemented into the song. Both choruses written by Jackson and Jam are used as the final two choruses.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/>|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nThe lyrics of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" were based on a poem Jackson found which she previously wrote and disposed of.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/jun/03/janet-jackson-10-of-the-best|title=Janet Jackson: 10 of the best|last=Cragg|first=Michael|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=June 3, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The poem's lyrics were kept intact, although its structure was altered. Jackson wrote further lyrics for the song during the same night Jam came up with the melody alongside drum programmer Alex Richburg. Initially conceived as a \"slow melody\", Jam chose to increase its [[tempo]]. Two different choruses were written by Jam and Jackson; Jam wrote \"Nutty, nutty, nutty, my love for you\" while Jackson wrote \"Doesn't really matter\". They decided to use Jackson's chorus, and include Jam's chorus towards the end of the track. Jackson presented three songs to Segal on May 12, 2000, three days prior to his set deadline for the soundtrack. He chose \"Doesn't Really Matter\", believing it was a better fit and a \"summertime record\". A slightly modified version was included on ''All for You'', featuring an alternate introduction and elements from the song's [[Rockwilder]] remix.<ref name=\"Bronson\" />\n\n==Composition==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" is lyrically inspired by Jackson's character in the film, who falls in love with Klump. According to Jackson, the lyrics are about Gaines' love for Klump and \"how it doesn't matter what is on the exterior, but the interior\",<ref name=\"Making\" /> with Jam stating that it is about what counts on the inside.<ref name=\"MTV\" /> The song has an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] sound, which is inspired by [[Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]]' digital [[funk]] production used in the discographies of [[TLC (group)|TLC]] and [[Destiny's Child]].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The track begins with a twenty-second \"breathy, mid-paced intro\", before transitioning into a \"spacious, electronic R&B club track\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> The dynamics also fluctuate, from stop-start verses leading to a double [[tempo]] chorus, to the mid-point breakdown eventually ending with the song's rapid conclusion.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' described \"Doesn't Really Matter\" as [[Burt Bacharach|Bacharachian]] with \"bells and whistles in the production\" and noted Jackson's \"falsetto trill\" on the lyrics \"My love / For you / Is unconditional too\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20267962,00.html|title=Now That's What I Call Music! 5|last=Farber|first=Jim|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 17, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1226514,00.html|title=Chart Flashback|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Pastorek|first=Whitney|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The magazine also pointed out the [[Half-time (music)|half-time]], [[Stutter edit|stutter-beat]] verse to the sung chorus,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=All for You Review|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|date=May 4, 2001}}</ref> which is complimented by the track's \"minimal percussive programming\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-all-for-you/94|title=Janet Jackson: All for You \u2013 Music Review|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=June 13, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]] called it an \"instant smash\" and \"impossibly catchy\", adding that the, \"public's appetite for Janet Jackson never wanes.\" Despite being \"the first new offering from Ms. Jackson in years,\" the song was thought to have \"the feel and sound of a young, girlish, naive Janet singing a happy pop song about love as opposed to the hardened, sexually experimental Janet who emerged during the later ''Velvet Rope'' years.\" The \"definitive\" song was qualified as \"classic pop Janet through and through\" and an \"essential\" hit.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doesnt-really-matter-us-cd5-cassette-mw0000101400 |title=Doesn't Really Matter [US CD5/Cassette]|work=[[AllMusic]] |last=Promis|first=Jose F. |date=August 8, 2000 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] commended the song for maintaining Jackson and her producers reputations as the \"leading lights of contemporary urban soul.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/all-for-you-mw0000017729 |title=All for You \u2013 Janet Jackson|work=[[AllMusic]] |last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas |date=April 24, 2001 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> AllMusic also reviewed several of the song's remixes, citing the \"[[Jonathan Peters]] Club Mix\" as the most superior; transforming the original into a \"summery, breezy dance record, complete with Spanish guitars and whistles.\" The review added \"The song lends itself surprisingly well to this transformation, and, with great instrumentation, results in a pleasant and effortless dance record.\" Rockwilder's \"Dance All Day Extended Mix\" was described as possessing a melodic [[hip-hop]] and \"[[dancehall]] flavor\", though was considered to lack the original's vibrancy. The \"Spensane Get Up Extended Mix\" has \"intense beats\" and accelerated production, making Jackson's vocals sound as if they are \"being played at 78 [[revolutions per minute|RPM]]\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Margo Whitmire hailed the \"dancey\" single as the year's \"standout summer track\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oRQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |title=Missing: A Summer Hit |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Whitmire|first=Margo |date=July 30, 2005 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> while [[Chuck Taylor (music journalist)|Chuck Taylor]] described the track as \"innocent fun\", returning to the \"ultra-pop side of Janet\" since \"[[Together Again (Janet Jackson song)|Together Again]]\". The song's \"radically different\" nature was thought to \"conjure a vibe\" of Jackson's hit \"[[Runaway (Janet Jackson song)|Runaway]]\", while its theme \"testifies that in all the world, love makes the most difference in life\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31|title=Reviews and Previews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|date=July 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' regarded it as Jackson's best single aside from \"[[Black Cat (song)|Black Cat]]\", saying that its \"subliminal Asianness\" aids Jackson's \"pretty\" voice in being \"fragile like [[rice paper]]\", comparing the song to [[Kyu Sakamoto]]'s 1963 song \"[[Sukiyaki (song)|Sukiyaki]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2001/03/13/backstabs-in-the-material-world/|title=Backstabs in the Material World|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last=Eddy|first=Chuck|date=March 13, 2001|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Entertainment Weekly'' called it \"effervescent\" and a standout, while ''[[New York Daily News]]'' considered it a \"breathy\" number from the \"shapely songbird\".<ref name=\"Daily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/gossip/capt-ted-familiar-port-call-article-1.865757|title=Capt. Ted's Familiar Port Of Call|website=[[New York Daily News]]|last=Molloy|first=Joanna|date=May 30, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64793,00.html|title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack Review|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Diehl|first=Matt|date=July 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The song received praise from ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'', saying it has \"a beat you just can't help but hum along to\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-08-04/entertainment/0008030478_1_nutty-professor-ii-buddy-love-klump|title=The Nutty Professor II: The Klumps|website=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Marschheuser|first=Melissa|date=August 4, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' considered it a \"comeback single\" for the \"pop queen\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-spice-girls/4092|title=New Spice!|website=[[NME]]|date=August 8, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223093352/http://www.nme.com/news/the-spice-girls/4092|archive-date=February 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> while ''[[CNN]]'' called it a \"pleasing single\", also labeled \"peppy, radio-perfect\" and \"funky fun\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0007/23/wbt.00.html|title=CNN Transcript \u2013 WorldBeat: Summer Music Festival Adds Flavor to Diverse Soundscape of Quebec; Ekova Gets Inspiration From All Corners of World \u2013 July 23, 2000|website=[[CNN]]|date=July 23, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[MTV News]] labeled it \"a return to Jackson's more melodic, pop side and a departure from the more groove-based ''The Velvet Rope''.\"<ref name=\"MTV\" /> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' called it \"blissful\" with a \"bright, shiny sound\", while MacKenzie Wilson of AllMusic considered it \"sweet upbeat\" and a large contrast from other songs on the film's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite book|date=April 10, 2001|title=\"Doesn't Really Matter\" review|website=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe Magazine]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA114|title=Vibe \u2013 Google Books|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|author=Kenner, Rob|date=April 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/nutty-professor-ii-the-klumps-mw0000069197|title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps \u2013 Original Soundtrack \u2013 Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards \u2013 AllMusic|work=AllMusic|last=Wilson|first=MacKenzie|date=June 23, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> It was also considered \"a less suffocating shade of pop\" for radio, both \"blippy\" and \"joyful\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-05-01/lifestyle/0104300241_1_janet-jackson-album-jackson-family-song|title=Janet Jackson Says Goodbye With A Bite|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|last=Piccoli|first=Sean|date=May 1, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emusic.com/music-news/connections/six-degrees-of-janet-jacksons-control/|title=Six Degrees of Janet Jackson's Control|work=EMusic|last=Johnston|first=Mauru|date=November 17, 2010|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Film magazine ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' described the song as \"soulful hip-pop\" and \"popcorn for the ears\", likening to \"vodka on the rocks\" for its \"[[Pepsi]] commercial\" semblance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=6315|title=Empire's Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack Review|website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire Online]]|year=2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222162945/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=6315|archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[About.com]] ranked it as the ninth best song of the year, calling it a \"midtempo classic\" and \"confident\".<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/top100lists/tp/top100songs2000.09.htm|title=Top 100 Pop Songs 2000|website=[[AllMusic]]|last=Lamb|first=Bill|year=2009|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/janetjacksoncme.htm|title=Janet Jackson with Nelly \u2013 Call On Me|website=[[Dotdash|About]]|last=Lamb|first=Bill|year=2009|access-date=February 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109034624/http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/janetjacksoncme.htm|archive-date=November 9, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was later ranked among the top one hundred best songs of the decade, considered \"one of the best examples of how Janet Jackson can make a hit single sound completely effortless,\" adding \"it did work for the movie, and it sounded fantastic on the radio as well.\"<ref name=\"Decade\">{{cite web |url=http://top40.about.com/od/top10lists/tp/top1002000s.01.htm |title=Top 100 Pop Songs of the 2000s, About.com Top 40 / Pop |work=[[Dotdash|About]]|last=Lamb|first=Bill|year=2009 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nAn [[Audio mastering|unmastered]] version of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" [[Internet leak|leaked]] ahead of its release date and received airplay from several radio stations who made their own edit from the leak, which pleased producer Jimmy Jam.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/971570/jimmy-jam-prepping-klumps-soundtrack.jhtml|title=Producer Jimmy Jam Readying 'Klumps' Soundtrack, Janet Jackson Album|work=[[MTV News]]|date=June 3, 2000|access-date=February 2, 2001}}</ref>. The song became Jackson's ninth number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on August 26, 2000, selling 96,000 units in its first week.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|date=August 26, 2000|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA106&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=101|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> It stayed on top for three consecutive weeks and was replaced by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celebrity9.com/janet-jackson/biography.html |title=Biography of Janet Jackson |work=Celebrity9 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> It made Jackson the first artist to achieve a number one single in the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s on the Hot 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6677541/rewinding-the-charts-15-years-ago-janet-jackson-scored-a-hot-100|title=Rewinding the Charts: 15 Years Ago, Janet Jackson Scored a Hot 100 First|last=Anderson|first=Trevor|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 26, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> and became Jackson's nineteenth single to receive a gold certification, and twenty-first single to be certified, ranking her as the second most successful female artist with the most certified singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|title=RIAA \u2013 Recording Industry Association of America|website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=February 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221215851/https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> It attained a silver certification in the United Kingdom, also receiving a [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]] Pop Award for Most Played Song and [[Japan Gold Disc Award]] for Top Selling Song of the Year by a foreign artist.<ref name=\"RIAJ\" /> The song peaked at number one on [[Top 40 Tracks]] and the [[Rhythmic Top 40]], three on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]], number nine on [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]], and number two in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/janet-jackson-mn0000208774|title=Janet Jackson \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography \u2013 AllMusic|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Huey, Steve|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"can\"/> \"Doesn't Really Matter\" achieved success internationally, reaching number five in the United Kingdom, number two on the [[UK R&B Chart]], the top ten in Italy and Denmark. It peaked within the top fifteen of Norway, Sweden, Belgium, and the Netherlands, and among the top twenty in Switzerland.\n\nUpon its release, it became the most added song on pop, rhythmic, and urban formats, also added to [[Hot Adult Contemporary]].<ref name=\"RandR\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2000/RR-2000-06-23.pdf|title=Janet And Friends|magazine=[[Radio & Records]]|number=1356|page=1|date=June 23, 2000}}</ref> The song was the first number one hit by a female artist on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 since [[Aaliyah]]'s \"[[Try Again (Aaliyah song)|Try Again]]\" several months earlier, breaking the longest streak of male acts at the chart's summit since eight years prior.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA106 |title=Oh Dear, What Can The 'Matter' Be? |work=Los Angeles Times |author=Bronson, Fred |date=August 26, 2000 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, ''Billboard'' ranked it the sixty-first most successful song by a female artist in the chart's history.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bronson |first=Fred |year=2007 |title=Billboard's Hottest Hot 100 Hits | work=Billboard Books}}</ref> The song's success allowed the film's soundtrack to open at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on the week of July 29, 2000, only behind [[Eminem]]'s ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]'', [[Britney Spears]]' ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!...I Did It Again]]'', and [[Nelly]]'s ''[[Country Grammar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2000-07-29|title=Billboard 200 \u2013 Week of July 29, 2000|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The album was later certified platinum on August 24, 2000, with over one million copies sold in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=nutty+professor+2&col=title&ord=asc#search_section|website=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]|title=Gold & Platinum \u2013 RIAA|access-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=328\n|image1=Akihabara Night.jpg\n|image2=Sony, aibo (cane robot), anni 2000 (ist. biorobotica polo sant'anna valdera).jpg\n|footer=The music video for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" is inspired by several elements from [[Japan]], such as the video's futuristic setting, and the [[AIBO]] that is seen near Jackson.\n}}\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], and takes place in a futuristic city resembling [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> The video was filmed during a turbulent period, in which Jackson was experiencing a divorce from unannounced husband [[Rene Elizondo, Jr.]], leading to intense media scrutiny and fluctuations in weight.<ref name=\"Making\"/> It shows Jackson in an [[abstract art|abstract]] [[anime]]-based environment, featuring an [[AIBO]], which was the very first consumer Artificial Intelligence robot and was created for the companionship of adults and elderly people. Morphing clothes, levitating platforms, and a futuristic [[Acura]] vehicle, the [[Acura CL]]-X Concept Prototype, are just a few of the other things featured in this video.<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> The music video was filmed in [[Los Angeles]] on June 4\u20135, and premiered on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Making the Video]]'' on June 28, 2000.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite episode|title=Janet Jackson: Doesn't Really Matter|series=[[Making the Video]]|network=[[MTV]]|date=June 28, 2000|season=3|number=2|language=en}}</ref> The video cost over $2.5 million, ranking it among the [[list of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos]] of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/most-expensive-music-videos/|title=The 5 Artists With the Most Expensive Music Videos of All Time|last=Bather|first=Luke|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKahn described the video's premise as \"epic minimalism\" in an attempt to differentiate from the large sets of other music videos. He wanted to create the video by using minimal sets, which would look larger in appearance.<ref name=\"Making\" /> Jackson was willing to collaborate with Kahn, stating that she enjoyed taking risks.<ref name=\"Making\" /> The outfits worn in the video was based on [[Japanese street fashion|fashion from Tokyo]].<ref name=\"Making\" /> One of the dancers in the video, [[Jenna Dewan]], got the role at the age of 19 as the only spot the choreographers were looking for.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8456679/jenna-dewan-janet-jackson-dancer-interview|title=Jenna Dewan on the Life-Changing Impact of Working With Janet Jackson: 'Once a Janet Dancer, Always a Janet Dancer'|last=Milzoff|first=Rebecca|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 18, 2018|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> All the dancers performed choreography on a moving platform as they were harnessed on bungee cords.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> Jackson stated that it \"tilts, slants, you can slide off or fall\".<ref name=\"Making\" /> The original scene was designed on a set, but was taken apart and replaced with a [[green screen]].<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=328\n|image1=Joseph kahn 01.jpg\n|image2=Jenna Dewan 2012.jpg\n|footer=Kahn studied Jackson's videos before becoming a director, while Dewan credited her appearance on the music video for being able to work with other artists.\n}}\n\nIn a 2014 interview with Video Static, Kahn praised his time working with Janet Jackson, acknowledging her work ethic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videostatic.com/interviews/2014/01/07/videostatic-interview-joseph-kahn |title=Talking Videos, Britney and more with Director Joseph Kahn |work=Video Static |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In an interview with ''Peel'' in 2000, he explained his experience in shooting the video with Jackson:<ref name=\"Kahn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.njs4ever.net/kahn3.html|title=An Interview With Joseph Kahn \u2013 Page Three|work=Peel|date=July 2000|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><blockquote>I was star struck on Janet for sure, because that was the first time that I really dealt with someone that was in my youth. I studied Janet Jackson videos growing up. So to finally see myself face to face with her and working with her and her calling me on a first name basis and calling my home and tracking me down on my cell phone[...] like her leaving messages, it was the weirdest thing[...] And Janet, she really is elegant, she's like royalty. Even though she's talking to you and trying to be normal, she's not \u2013 she's Janet Jackson \u2013 and you can never get that out of your head. You realize that she's a real person and she's got just the same emotions as everyone else, but you can never get around the fact that she's special.</blockquote>\n\nThe music video was one of the first appearances by Dewan, who stated \"I was fortunate enough to work with Janet who treats her dancers amazing,\" describing it as her most memorable video shoot.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/timberlakes-ex-blood-37259.aspx|title=Timberlake's Ex Is Out for Blood|work=[[TV Guide]]|last=Webb|first=Matt|date=February 17, 2006|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> After the shoot wrapped, Dewan was personally offered the role as one of Jackson's tour dancers in the All for You Tour by Jackson herself, dancing for her for two straight years.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> She credited working with Jackson in the video, as well as \"[[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\" and the All for You Tour, for allowing her to later work with other major artists.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/>\n\n===Reception===\nThe video's premise, portraying Jackson as she \"romps around with some girlfriends in a futuristic setting\" and \"getting freaky in Tokyo\", was praised for its variation from standard \"lip-synch/film snippet formula\" used among pop videos at the time. It was also \"happily free\" of scenes from its accompanying film, saying the clip \"stands on its own\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdmg.com/klumpsuncensored.shtml |title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps \u2013 Uncensored Director's Cut (2000) |work=DVD Movie Guide |author=Jacobson, Colin|year=2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[DVD Talk]] likened the video's setting to [[science fiction film]] ''[[The Fifth Element]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/1275/nutty-professor-2-the-klumps/|title=Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps : DVD Talk Review of the DVD Video |work=[[DVD Talk]]|last=Beierle|first=Aaron|date=November 11, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The video's popularity saw the AIBO ERS-210 robotic dog generate increased market demand and commercial success, after the \"bionic beast got to snuggle up to Janet Jackson\" in the clip.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/01/03/business/let-aibo-tell-you-about-brand-image/ |title=Let Aibo tell you about brand image \u2013 The Japan Times |work=Japan Times |author=Gilhooly, Rob|year=2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Sun Sentinel]]'' included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" among several videos which set fashion trends and increased the popularity of \"must-have colors\" in clothing among youth. The vibrant \"red and orange\" outfits worn by Jackson, including \"sugary pinks and orange tees\", items from the ''Self Esteem'' line, and \"designer duds right off the runway,\" were described to heighten demand for similar \"bright colorful clothes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-08-08/lifestyle/0008070457_1_colors-young-women-video|title=What Are The Coolest Kids Wearing This Fall? Fiery Reds And Blazing Oranges Because They Are . . .|work=[[The Sun Sentinel]]|last=Hagwood|first=Rod Stafford|date=August 8, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Matthew Trammell of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' noted that the music video's influence of consumer technology consequentially led to the popularity of [[Siri]] and [[Amazon Alexa|Alexa]] in pop culture.<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/11/20/janet-jacksons-doesnt-really-matter-music-video-saw-the-future?verso=true|title=Janet Jackson's \"Doesn't Really Matter\" Music Video Saw The Future|last=Trammell|first=Matthew|website=[[The New Yorker]]|date=November 10, 2017|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> He also stated that the 2020 re-production of the AIBO model in Japan meant that the world is \"closer to the bulbous, pastel metropolis conjured by Janet Jackson in one of the most forward-leaning music videos of its time\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\nJackson performed \"Doesn't Really Matter\" on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' on August 4, 2000,<ref>{{cite episode|series=[[Top of the Pops]]|network=[[BBC One]]|series-number=37|number=32|date=August 4, 2000|language=en}}</ref> and the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]] on September 7, 2000.<ref name=\"VMAs\"/> Jackson opened the show in a black leather outfit in an aerial set among multiple backing dancers. Her long hair was obscuring her face for much of the performance.<ref name=\"VMAs\">{{cite web|last=Basham|first=David|url=http://www.sonicnet.com:80/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|title=VMA Report #2: Janet Jackson Kicks Off Night's Performances|publisher=Sonicnet|accessdate=December 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001209075800/http://www.sonicnet.com/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|archivedate=December 9, 2000|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' stated Jackson made \"a rare TV performance\" featuring a \"three-tiered set and ten backing dancers\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Style Beats Substance Among Artists At Video Music Awards|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Abott|first=Jim|date=September 8, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 and 2002, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was included on the [[All for You Tour]] as the encore.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> For the performance, she wore demure white tee and jeans. ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' considered the rendition \"jubilant and \"spirited\", while MTV News called it \"a fully [[Motion picture rating system|PG]] Janet\".<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ms-janet-jackson-gets-nasty-20010710|title=Ms. Janet Jackson Gets Nasty|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 10, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mtv.com/news/article.rbml?id=1445013 |title=MTV Mobile News: Janet Jackson Live: Tears, Bondage And Tupac|work=[[MTV News]]|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=July 9, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221203150/http://m.mtv.com/news/article.rbml?id=1445013|archivedate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> A writer for ''New York Daily News'' said Jackson performed a \"stripped-down \"Doesn't Really Matter\" with no choreography or dance troupe to hide behind.\" The tour's performance was also praised for allowing Jackson to appear \"looser\", which effectively \"cut the self-consciousness and relaxed into more natural moves\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-10-26/entertainment/0110240916_1_jackson-s-new-music-janet-jackson-tours/2 |title=Just Call Her The Diva Next Door \u2013 Page 2 \u2013 Sun Sentinel |work=Sun Sentinel |date=October 26, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/janet-find-article-1.932368#ixzz2tCK2UlPc|title=Janet's All For You, If You Can Find Her|work=[[New York Daily News]]|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=August 21, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Jam! Canoe]]'' considered the tour's performance \"upbeat and warm\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/J/Jackson_Janet/ConcertReviews/2004/09/25/pf-643658.html |title=CANOE -- JAM! - Air Canada Centre, Toronto \u2013 August 2, 2001 |author=Stevenson, Jane |work=Canoe Jam! |date=August 3, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor her first concert tour in six years, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was included on the 2008 [[Rock Witchu Tour]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/janet-jackson-opens-rock-witchu-tour-with-three-decades-of-hits-video-duets-and-pyro-20080911 |title=Janet Jackson Opens Rock Witchu Tour With Three Decades of Hits |date=September 11, 2008 |accessdate=September 9, 2014|last=Sheppard|first=Denise |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> During the [[Number Ones, Up Close and Personal]] world tour, she wore black jeans and a tank top to perform the song. ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the performance saying \"it's the closest she gets to representing life as lived rather than as performed\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/21/arts/music/janet-jacksons-number-ones-at-radio-city-review.html?_r=1& |title=Janet Jackson's 'Number Ones' at Radio City \u2013 Review \u2013 NYTimes.com |work=New York Times |author=Ratliff, Ben |date=March 20, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Jackson dedicated the song to the audience while performing in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepowerplayermag.com/Archive/PPMApril11/Thepowerplayermag/Events.html |title=Events|work=PowerPlayerLifestyle|date=April 8, 2011|access-date=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807062326/http://www.thepowerplayermag.com/Archive/PPMApril11/Thepowerplayermag/Events.html |archivedate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> The song's music video was played on screens preceding the opening number for selected dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/ocregister-481692-http-soundcheck.html |title=Janet Jackson in top form heading into L.A. gigs|work=Orange County Register |date=April 11, 2011 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Jackson included the song on her second leg of the 2018 [[State of the World Tour]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|title=Janet Jackson turns Syracuse into dance party with a message (review, photos)|url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2018/07/janet_jackson_syracuse_concert_review.html|date=August 10, 2018|publisher=Scene|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> as well as on her 2019 Las Vegas residency, [[Janet Jackson: Metamorphosis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|title=Janet Jackson Draws Queen Latifah, Eve & More to ''Metamorphosis'' Residency Opening in Las Vegas |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8512088/janet-jackson-metamorphosis-las-vegas-residency-opening-review|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|date=May 20, 2019|access-date=January 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Covers and usage in popular culture==\nJapanese singer [[Hitomi Shimatani]] covered the song under the title \"Papillon\", which sold over 200,000 copies, and made her become one of the top artists on the [[Avex Trax]] label.<ref name=\"Avex\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpopasia.com/celebrity/hitomishimatani/ |title=Hitomi Shimatani's bio \u2013 singer \u2013 jpop |work=JPopAsia|year=2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Shimatani was presented the idea to cover the song due to its success, saying \"the song had a big impact\" and was \"played repeatedly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jame-world.com/us/articles-3517-an-interview-with-shimatani-hitomi.html |title=An interview with Shimatani Hitomi \u2013 JaMe U.S.A. |work=JaME World |date=December 12, 2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[N\u00e9stor Torres]] recorded a jazz version of the song for his seventh album ''This Side of Paradise''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-08-26/news/0208260048_1_nestor-torres-latin-grammy-band |title=A Romantic, Energetic Evening From Nestor Torres |work=The Courant |date=August 26, 2002 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsweek]]'' considered [[Rihanna]]'s \"[[Watch n' Learn]]\", from her sixth studio album ''[[Talk that Talk]]'', an \"answer to Janet Jackson's \"Doesn't Really Matter\" due to its similar production and \"playful\" nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/rihanna-s-talk-is-another-winner-1.3332047|title=Rihanna's 'Talk' is another winner|website=[[Newsweek]]|last=Gamoba|first=Glenn|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> ''Billboard'' likened Destiny's Child to being influenced by Jackson's strategy of releasing a soundtrack single shortly before an album campaign with \"Doesn't Really Matter\" for \"[[Independent Women]],\" saying the group \"began planting the seeds for the upcoming release\" in a similar vein.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA146|title=Between the Bullets|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Mayfield|first=Geoff|date=August 12, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe song was used in the international arcade releases of the ''[[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNova]]'' series and ''[[Dance Dance Revolution X]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNova]]|developer=[[Konami]]|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=2006|platform=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]}}</ref> In 2012, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] political strategist [[Richard Socarides]] selected \"Doesn't Really Matter\" for a live playlist on [[CNN]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://startingpoint.blogs.cnn.com/2012/08/01/starting-point-playlist-for-wednesday-august-1-2012/ |title=Starting Point playlist for Wednesday, August 1, 2012 \u2013 Starting Point |work=Starting Point |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=August 1, 2012 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In September 2013, [[record producer]] and [[radio personality]] [[Mister Cee]] included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" blended with [[Maino]]'s \"[[Hi Hater]]\" during a live set upon his return to famed [[New York City|New York]] radio station [[WQHT|Hot 97]] following several solicitation allegations, saying \"Just listen to the words.\" The inclusion of Jackson's song was considered to subliminally reveal his bisexuality, called the set's \"most triumphant moment\", and a response to critics in opposition of his sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/09/mister-cee-hot-97-resign-first-mix/ |title=Embattled DJ Mister Cee Returns to Hot 97 With Hour-Long 'Can I Live' Subtweet \u2013 Spin \u2013 Newswire |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=September 12, 2013 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Australian CD single {{small|(5629152)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=162597 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter Australia 5\" CD SINGLE (162597)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><br>\n'''Japanese CD single {{small|(UICD-5001)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=162609 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter Japan 5\" CD SINGLE (162609)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><br>\n'''Taiwanese CD single {{small|(562915-2)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=250741 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter Taiwan 5\" CD SINGLE (250741)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n# Radio Edit \u2013 4:00\n# Rockwilder Mix \u2013 5:04\n# Jonathan Peters Club Mix \u2013 8:49\n# Doesn't Really Matter (Video)\n{{col-2}}\n'''UK 12\" single {{small|(5629161)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=168793 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter UK 12\" RECORD/MAXI SINGLE (168793)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n# Radio Edit \u2013 4:00\n# Rockwilder Mix \u2013 5:04\n# Jonathan Peters Club Mix \u2013 8:49\n# Instrumental \u2013 4:37\n# Spensane Get Up Extended Mix \u2013 6:33\n# Jonathan Peters Sound Factory Dub \u2013 8:31\n{{col-2}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:70%;\"\n|-\n! width=\"25%\" scope=\"col\" | Award\n! width=\"50%\" scope=\"col\" | Nominated work\n! width=\"20%\" scope=\"col\" | Result\n! width=\"5%\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[About.com]]\n|Top 100 Best Pop Songs of 2000 \u2013 #9\n|{{n/a}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"About\" />\n|-\n|[[About.com]]\n|Top 100 Pop Songs of the Decade \u2013 #86\n|{{n/a}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"About\" />\n|-\n|[[Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]]\n|Favorite Song from a Movie\n|{{nom}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1438595/destinys-child-lead-blockbuster-nominees/|title=Destiny's Child Lead Blockbuster Nominees|author=Eric Schumacer Rasmussen|website=[[MTV News]]|date=January 29, 2001|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]] Pop Awards\n|Most Performed Song from a Motion Picture\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Pesselnick|first=Jill|date=May 26, 2001|title=Walden Wins BMI Prize|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=bmi+pop+awards+doesn%27t+really+matter&source=bl&ots=VYZyD-b0dn&sig=ACfU3U2k00IXeyL7upJ5lg82vmZ6nhYpAA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwin0tKB-fLmAhWAxDgGHYaOCKQQ6AEwCnoECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=bmi%20pop%20awards%20doesn't%20really%20matter&f=false|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Japan Gold Disc Award]]s\n|Top Selling Song of the Year \u2013 Foreign Music\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"RIAJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2001.html|title=Recording Industry Association of Japan \u2013 Related Data|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan|RIAJ]]|access-date=April 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031220134721/http://www.riaj.or.jp/e/data/gdisc/2001.html|archive-date=December 20, 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[VH1]] Fashion Awards\n|Most Stylish Music Video\n|{{won}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/insidevh1/events/fashion2000/stylish.jhtml|title=Most Stylish Video|website=[[VH1]]|access-date=August 30, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001018034311/http://www.vh1.com/insidevh1/events/fashion2000/stylish.jhtml|archive-date=October 18, 2000 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2000)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|28|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|28|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|13|artist=Janet Jackson|song=Doesn't Really Matter|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2011}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|2|chartid=709